  "prompt": "Can somebody explain how time is relative in layman's terms?",
  "response": "Sure! The idea of time being relative comes from Albert Einstein's theory of relativity. Here\u2019s a simple way to understand it:\n\n1. **Different Speeds**: Imagine two people, one standing still and the other moving very fast\u2014like in a spaceship. According to Einstein, the person in the spaceship experiences time differently than the person on the ground. If they were to meet again after a long journey, the person in the spaceship would have aged less than the person who stayed on Earth. This is called \"time dilation.\"\n\n2. **Gravity's Effect**: Time is also affected by gravity. The closer you are to a massive object (like a planet), the slower time moves for you compared to someone farther away. So, if you were on a mountain (where gravity is slightly weaker) and a friend was at sea level, time would pass a tiny bit faster for you on the mountain.\n\n3. **Everyday Example**: Think of time as a rubber band. If you stretch it (like moving really fast or being near a massive object), it changes how you experience it compared to someone who isn't stretching it.\n\nIn short, time isn't fixed for everyone; it can stretch or shrink based on how fast you're moving or how much gravity you're experiencing.",
